post_text: CMHS will be administering the school day SAT on Wednesday, September 23. Only students classified as grade 12 will be in attendance to take the SAT. Completion of the state SAT is a graduation requirement, so attendance is extremely important on this day. There will be no Remote Learning scheduled for all students on this day. Bus pickup times and locations will be posted under the Busing tab in Skyward Family Access. Students will be required to wear masks at all times while on the bus and while in the school building. They will also complete a Wellness Screening and have their temperature scanned upon entry to CMHS. Please make sure you bring a photo ID, number 2 pencils (not mechanical), and a calculator. Cell phones should be left at home on this day. Good luck to all of our students! #CMHSWarriors #CMHS #cm201u

Update for Balmoral families:
As you prepare for remote learning, this is a list of items that most scholars will need available at home: headphones, 1 box of pencils (12), 1 or 2 boxes of crayons, 1 pair of scissors, 1 pack of index cards, 1 pack of black Expo markers, 2 or 3 wide-ruled spirals, 1 box of markers, 2 or 3 glue sticks, 1 large pink eraser, 1 or 2 folders, 1 highlighter, 1 personal pencil sharpener.

An altered supply list for when we move into hybrid learning is available on our school website.

-District-issued Chromebook
-Headphones/earbuds with a microphone
-Scientific calculator (TI 30 is recommended)
-Paper. Both lined and unlined.
-Writing utensils including pencils, pens and coloring items
-Textbooks, planner, and any other materials provided by the school during pick-up.

Looking for your start of the school year items? CM School District is hard at work to provide you with all the information you'll need to get your student's school year started right! The following items will be available tomorrow, August 27th:

- SITE PLANS (Individual school plans for the new school year) will be posted to your school's webpage.
- SUPPLY LISTS (Items your student will need for the 20-21 school year) will be posted to your school's webpage & Facebook.
- TEACHER LIST (Names of your student's teachers) will be uploaded to Skyward Family Access.

If you have any questions, please reach out to your school's principal. We appreciate your patience as we work hard to make this a safe and successful school year for us all!

post_text: DISTRICT SCHOOLS TO REOPEN REMOTELY ON AUGUST 31: Please take a moment to review the District's Opening With Equity Plan for the reopening of schools. Dr. Coglianese presented the plan to reopen schools remotely from August 31-October 19, 2020 at last night's board meeting. The Hybrid A/B Model will begin October 19, 2020, which is a blended model of instruction that uses both Traditional Learning and Remote Learning. View the presentation at https://buff.ly/32WW3o7

post_text: Ms. VanHootegem from Talala Elementary is so proud of her 4th grade class! During remote learning, the students had the opportunity to learn a variety of technology skills using their Chromebooks. Students learned how to take photos, make videos, create slide presentations, present their screens during Google Meets, use Jamboard as a virtual whiteboard and so much more! This knowledge allowed them to create a classroom recipe book, host Google Meets, create a class yearbook filled with bitmojis and we also just had fun together playing Pictionary using Jamboard. These students really made the most of their remote learning time. Look out 5th grade, HERE THEY COME!

post_text: Talala first grader's in Mrs. Lanning's class took a virtual field trip to the zoo. The students could click on an "animal habitat" which took them to a slide where they could learn more about the animal, how to draw it, and sometimes even see a live feed of the animal. Students in the class also served as the zookeepers. They researched their animal by reading a book on Epic! and then made some of the slides for the habitats. The students enjoyed this fun and interactive way to learn more about animals at the zoo.

post_text: CSK fifth grade teachers wanted to have a little fun with their students on this dark and dreary day. As part of their science unit, Mixtures & Solutions, they had students use items from their kitchens to create "lava in a cup." The experiment focused on density. Students observed what happened when they put oil into water then add salt. It created bubbles, or a lava lamp effect! #remotelearning

post_text: COVID-19 has changed the way we Relay. But with everyone’s support, we can make sure the fight to end cancer doesn’t stop. The “normal” Relay For Life at CMHS might have not taken place, but the student Event Leadership Team, including Juniors Alyssa Haton and Kaeli Rinkin and Freshman Kameron Casper wanted to still carry on. Because CANCER NEVER SLEEPS. Now more than ever the American Cancer Society mission is vital to cancer patients and families everywhere. So, on Sunday, May 24, join us throughout the day on all the virtual channels as we bring Relay For Life right to you! And the whole community is invited! You may dedicate a Luminaria, you can share a picture of yourself and a loved when telling us Why I Relay, you can be a sponsor, you can go live anytime during the day and “walk” with us. For further information email heidi.gonzalez@cancer.org

post_text:
Happy School Communicator Day!

The unsung heroes behind the scenes of every effective organization is a great school communicator. You may be asking what does a school communicator actually do? Well, here are a few tasks…and yes, some are actually all done by noon each day.

o Write communication newsletters
o Create PowerPoint presentations with graphics
o Attends meetings to capture essential information to share
o Publish press releases
o Respond to news reporters and editors about the latest updates with emergencies or topics of crisis
o Manage all social media accounts, reading each and every comment
o Coordinate website updates
o Create brochures, flyers, banners, signs, and informational narratives for initiative rollouts
o And….still managing to keep a great sense of humor through it all.

Thank you, Mrs. Natalie Nash, for being such a fantastic school communicator for the Crete-Monee 201U School District! You’re one in a million!

shared_text:
Will County Health Department
April 16 at 3:11 PM ·

TEXT TALK to 552020
TEXT HABLAR to 552020
"During these stressful times of the Coronavirus pandemic, and all the life challenges that have come with it, the WCHD (Will County Health Department) Behavioral Health (BH) division is now able to offer residents a chance to have a mental health professional to talk to, free of charge, when things become overwhelming."
This past Saturday, April 11th, Governor Pritzker announced that the CALL4CALM line had been activated by the State of Illinois. As part of the DMH Program initiative, any text or call made to the CALL4CALM number from within Will County will be directed to the WCHD BH division. Thank you to all of our Essential Workers continuing to do their part to improve health!

post_text: CSK's fifth grade is learning about multiplying fractions and put it to a practical use today! They doubled a recipe for banana bread and Ms. Farris went live and made a double batch of banana bread based on the computations from the students. They covered the math skill of multiplying fractions, reviewed volume talking about different pans that Ms. Farris had to use, and learned about functional writing used when writing a recipe.

Now is a better time than ever to stay active, stay connected, and come together as a school and community **VIRTUALLY.**

TO JOIN:
1) Rock your best CMHS gear.
2) Complete a 5k (3.1 miles) by walking, running, biking, blading any time between Monday 4/13- Saturday 4/18.
3) Snap a selfie and your results and send it to smythk@cm201u.org.

Each coach will donate $1 per completed 5k to a local charity assisting COVID-19 first responders.

All CM 201-U buildings will remain closed. Phone calls will be transferred remotely between 9:00 a.m. - 3:00 p.m. Please continue to follow all recommendations to keep your family safe. Thank you!

post_text:
PLEASE NOTE: The date has been extended to April 7, 2020.
The district is committed to ensuring all of our students eat a proper breakfast and lunch during this time.

The Food Service Department will begin serving FREE breakfast and lunch to district families regardless of income on Wednesday, March 18 - Tuesday, April 7 from 8:00 a.m. - 10:30 a.m. Children need not be present for meal pick up. Please drive up to Door 12 at the Administration Center at 1500 Sangamon in Crete.

Please note we will also offer breakfast and lunch to the general public. There will be a nominal fee of $2 for breakfast and $3 for lunch for those over the age of 18.

Please check the website at buff.ly/2ybQUbk for the Spring Break Schedule.

Questions? Please contact Pamela Pansa, Director of Food Service (pansap@cm201u.org).

We look forward to serving you!

A Message from Ms. Triche, CMHS Principal: I understand these are uncertain times for all of us, and it feels like we're living through a novel right now. Please know the administration team at CMHS will continue to be there for you, our students, and the community. My secretary, Ms. Cynthia Rodriguez, came across this video series after sorting through the resources we received from a presentation last week. Please view it when you have time and know my thoughts are with you and your families.

Rooted in Love is a video sponsored by Jostens Renaissance Education; they typically provide resources to support positive culture and climate in the schools. After watching this video, I felt it was needed and necessary to share with the CMHS community at large. I understand these are challenging times, and together we will see our way through this. https://buff.ly/2IWJYUn

The Food Service Department will begin serving FREE breakfast and lunch to district families regardless of income on Wednesday, March 18 - Friday, March 27th from 8:00 a.m. - 10:30 a.m. Children need not be present for meal pick up. Please drive up to Door 12 at the Administration Center at 1500 Sangamon in Crete.

Please note we will also offer breakfast and lunch to the general public. There will be a nominal fee of $2 for breakfast and $3 for lunch for those over the age of 18.

text:
The district will begin a government-mandated closure of schools tomorrow, Tuesday, March 17. The district is committed to ensuring all of our students eat a proper breakfast and lunch during this time.

The Food Service Department will begin serving FREE breakfast and lunch to district families regardless of income on Wednesday, March 18 - Friday, March 27th from 8:00 a.m. - 10:30 a.m. Children need not be present for meal pick up. Please drive up to Door 12 at the Administration Center at 1500 Sangamon in Crete.

Please note we will also offer breakfast and lunch to the general public. There will be a nominal fee of $2 for breakfast and $3 for lunch for those over the age of 18.

Please check the website at www.CM201U.org for the Spring Break Schedule.

Questions? Please contact Pamela Pansa, Director of Food Service (pansap@cm201u.org).

We look forward to serving you!

post_text:
Posted March 13, 2020 at 4:46 P.M.: GOVERNOR ORDERS SCHOOL CLOSURE

At 3:53 p.m. this afternoon, Governor J.B. Pritzker ordered the closure of all state schools beginning Tuesday, March 17 through March 30. The earliest our students could return is Monday, April 6th due to Spring Break. Supt. Coglianese intends to share the school closure plan with you via a video message that will outline details of our plans on Monday afternoon at 3 p.m. via our website and social media.

While we understand any anxiety and uncertainty you may be feeling, we want to assure you that we are sensitive to your concerns. We want you to know that, together, we will get through this difficult time. Please remember that we are a community of WARRIORS and continue to take care of each other.

post_text:
This morning Crete-Monee Middle School conducted a soft lockdown and canine search of the building. The lockdown has concluded and the building is back to normal activity. Students were not approached and there was minimum disruption to the learning environment.

Random and unannounced canine sweeps offer a proactive approach to keeping our school safe and we are pleased to report that officers found no contraband during their search of the building. Thank you.

post_text: The South Suburban Small Business Association recognized a few of our young entrepreneurs enrolled in our Small Business Management classes. Ronyae Spearmon, Elijah Lawson, and Lakayla Kimble were among the few young entrepreneurs that were recognized and received awards at the 18th Annual Summit Awards Breakfast on February 12, 2020 at the Idlewild Country Club in Flossmoor. Ronyae Spearmon received the Young Entrepreneur of the Year award. This award recognizes the vision, innovation and hard work of a young person; their contributions to the community; and raises awareness among our youth that private enterprise and entrepreneurship play in the building of America. The Small Business Management teacher, Ms. Beverly Brown, Principal Marjorie Triche, and Superintendent Dr. Kara Coglianese were in attendance to witness this great honor be bestowed to these up and coming entrepreneurs.
